Larvae Biomineralization Block 1

coefvariation<- function(x){
  sd(x,na.rm=T)/abs(mean(x, na.rm=T))
}

logitTransform<- function(p){
  log(p/(1-p))
}

#test to see if tanks are significantly different. 
boxplot(SatArag_ATDIC~Tank, data=Tank_WCB1, na.omit=TRUE)

#check for significant differences in saturation state between tanks within treatments
Ca1<- lmer(SatArag_ATDIC~ParentTrt + (1|Tank), data=Tank_WCB1)
## boundary (singular) fit: see ?isSingular
Ca2<- lmer(SatArag_ATDIC~ 1 + (1|Tank), data= Tank_WCB1)
anova(Ca1, Ca2) #select Ca1
## refitting model(s) with ML (instead of REML)

## refitting model(s) with ML (instead of REML)
## Data: Tank_WCB1

#check assumptions
par(mfcol=c(2,2))
plot(Ca3) #seems to meet assumptions of homoscedasticity and linearity. 

shapiro.test(resid(Ca3)) #meets assumption of normality. 
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  resid(Ca3)
## W = 0.95269, p-value = 0.5335
par(mfcol=c(1,1))
acf(resid(Ca3)) #this looks good.

Remove egg outliers

#check for outliers using code from https://www.r-bloggers.com/identify-describe-plot-and-remove-the-outliers-from-the-dataset/. The function uses Tukey's method to ID ouliers ranged above and below the 1.5*IQR. 
outlierKD <- function(dt, var) {
     var_name <- eval(substitute(var),eval(dt))
     na1 <- sum(is.na(var_name))
     m1 <- mean(var_name, na.rm = T)
     par(mfrow=c(2, 2), oma=c(0,0,3,0))
     boxplot(var_name, main="With outliers")
     hist(var_name, main="With outliers", xlab=NA, ylab=NA)
     outlier <- boxplot.stats(var_name)$out
     mo <- mean(outlier)
     var_name <- ifelse(var_name %in% outlier, NA, var_name)
     boxplot(var_name, main="Without outliers")
     hist(var_name, main="Without outliers", xlab=NA, ylab=NA)
     title("Outlier Check", outer=TRUE)
     na2 <- sum(is.na(var_name))
     cat("Outliers identified:", na2 - na1, "n")
     cat("Propotion (%) of outliers:", round((na2 - na1) / sum(!is.na(var_name))*100, 1), "n")
     cat("Mean of the outliers:", round(mo, 2), "n")
     m2 <- mean(var_name, na.rm = T)
     cat("Mean without removing outliers:", round(m1, 2), "n")
     cat("Mean if we remove outliers:", round(m2, 2), "n")
     response <- readline(prompt="Do you want to remove outliers and to replace with NA? [yes/no]: ")
     if(response == "y" | response == "yes"){
          dt[as.character(substitute(var))] <- invisible(var_name)
          assign(as.character(as.list(match.call())$dt), dt, envir = .GlobalEnv)
          cat("Outliers successfully removed", "n")
          return(invisible(dt))
     } else{
          dt[as.character(substitute(var))] <- invisible(var_name)
          assign(as.character(as.list(match.call())$dt), dt, envir = .GlobalEnv)
          cat("Outliers successfully removed", "n")
          return(invisible(dt))
     }
}
outlierKD(EggsB1, EggDiamum) #I opted to remove outliers for now.

Get Jar Chemistry to add to Carb summary table

#add the jar chemistry
CarbChemJar<- subset(LarvByJarDat, select= c("Trt", "BottleChemistry", "JarpHNBS", "JarpHSW", "JarSalinity", "JarTemp", "JarDICCorr", "JarATCorr", "JarATCalc_SW", "JarpCO2_SW", "JarHCO3_SW", "JarCO3_SW", "JarCO2_SW", "JarSatCalcite_SW", "JarSatArg_SW" ))
JarChemMean<- ddply(CarbChemJar, .(Trt), numcolwise(mean, na.rm=T)) 
JarChemMean[,c(2,3)]<- round(JarChemMean[,c(2,3)], 2) #round pHs to two decimal places. 
JarChemMean[,c(13,14)]<- round(JarChemMean[,c(13,14)],3) #round saturation states to three decimal places.
JarChemMean[,c(6:12)]<- round(JarChemMean[,c(6:12)]) #round AT, DIC, pCO2, CO3, Co2, and HCO3 to no decimal places. 
JarChemMean[,c(4,5)]<- round(JarChemMean[,c(4,5)], 1) #round temp and salinity to one decimal places. 

JarChemSD<- ddply(CarbChemJar, .(Trt), numcolwise(sd, na.rm=T)) 
JarChemSD[,c(2,3)]<- round(JarChemSD[,c(2,3)], 2) #round pHs to two decimal places. 
JarChemSD[,c(13,14)]<- round(JarChemSD[,c(13,14)],3) #round saturation states to three decimal places.
JarChemSD[,c(6:12)]<- round(JarChemSD[,c(6:12)]) #round AT, DIC, pCO2, CO3, Co2, and HCO3 to no decimal places. 
JarChemSD[,c(4,5)]<- round(JarChemSD[,c(4,5)], 1) #round temp and salinity to one decimal places. 
JarChemMin<- ddply(CarbChemJar, .(Trt), numcolwise(min, na.rm=T)) 
JarChemMin[,c(2,3)]<- round(JarChemMin[,c(2,3)], 2) #round pHs to two decimal places. 
JarChemMin[,c(13,14)]<- round(JarChemMin[,c(13,14)],3) #round saturation states to three decimal places.
JarChemMin[,c(6:12)]<- round(JarChemMin[,c(6:12)]) #round AT, DIC, pCO2, CO3, Co2, and HCO3 to no decimal places. 
JarChemMin[,c(4,5)]<- round(JarChemMin[,c(4,5)], 1) #round temp and salinity to one decimal places. 
JarChemMax<- ddply(CarbChemJar, .(Trt), numcolwise(max, na.rm=T)) 
JarChemMax[,c(2,3)]<- round(JarChemMax[,c(2,3)], 2) #round pHs to two decimal places. 
JarChemMax[,c(13,14)]<- round(JarChemMax[,c(13,14)],3) #round saturation states to three decimal places.
JarChemMax[,c(6:12)]<- round(JarChemMax[,c(6:12)]) #round AT, DIC, pCO2, CO3, Co2, and HCO3 to no decimal places. 
JarChemMax[,c(4,5)]<- round(JarChemMax[,c(4,5)], 1) #round temp and salinity to one decimal places. 
#rename columns
colnames(JarChemSD)<- paste(colnames(JarChemSD),"sd", sep="_")
colnames(JarChemMin)<- paste(colnames(JarChemMin),"min", sep="_")
colnames(JarChemMax)<- paste(colnames(JarChemMax),"max", sep="_")

#merge all of the jar data together. 
JarCarbChem<- merge(JarChemMean, JarChemSD, by.x="Trt", by.y="Trt_sd") %>% 
  merge(JarChemMin, by.x="Trt", by.y="Trt_min") %>% 
  merge(JarChemMax, by.x="Trt", by.y= "Trt_max") %>% 
  t() %>% 
  as.data.frame()
colnames(JarCarbChem)<- paste(c("LarvaeControl", "LarvaeExposed"))
#write the csv to get the parameters for the carb table for Jars
write.csv(JarCarbChem,"~/R/GitHub/LarvaeTransGen2018/data/JarCarbChemSummary.csv")

Do simple t-tests on the means for oa-exposed and control exposed parents within each larvae treatment

#get Bonferoni adjusted p-crit: 
0.05/10
## [1] 0.005

Lcon<- subset(LarvaeDat, JarTrt=="Control")
